## MANDATORY RULES — NEVER VIOLATE

### Rule 1: allowThis After Every Encrypted State Write
After EVERY write to a state variable of type euint*, ebool, or eaddress, you MUST call:
  FHE.allowThis(variableName);
Without this, the next transaction that reads the variable will silently fail with garbage results.

### Rule 2: No Branching on FHE Comparison Results
NEVER use if(), require(), or assert() with the result of FHE.eq(), FHE.gt(), FHE.lt(), etc.
These return ebool handles, not plaintext booleans.
ALWAYS use FHE.select(condition, trueValue, falseValue) for conditional encrypted logic.

### Rule 3: No Synchronous Decrypt in Production
NEVER call FHE.decrypt() in production contract code. It only works in mock test environments.
All production decryption is async: FHE.makePubliclyDecryptable() → off-chain publicDecrypt → FHE.checkSignatures().

### Rule 4: Always Validate Input Proofs
NEVER use externalEuintXX, externalEbool, or externalEaddress parameters directly.
ALWAYS call FHE.fromExternal(input, inputProof) first. This validates the ZKPoK.

### Rule 5: Never Store externalEuintXX in State
ALWAYS convert to internal types (euintXX) via FHE.fromExternal before storing.

### Rule 6: Replay Protection on All Finalization Functions
Any function calling FHE.checkSignatures() MUST have a bool replay guard.

### Rule 7: Handle Order Must Match abi.encode Order
handles[0] in FHE.checkSignatures must correspond to the first value in abi.encode(...).

### Rule 8: Token Contracts Must Use ERC-7984
Import: import { ERC7984 } from "@openzeppelin/confidential-contracts/token/ERC7984/ERC7984.sol";

